.PP
This module was written for one-to-many style sockets (type \fIseqpacket\fR). With the addition of \fIpeeloff/2\fR, one-to-one style sockets (type \fIstream\fR) were introduced.

.PP
Record definitions for this module can be found using:

.IP
.nf
-include_lib("kernel/include/inet_sctp.hrl").

.fi

.PP
These record definitions use the "new" spelling 'adaptation', not the deprecated 'adaption', regardless of which spelling the underlying C API uses.

.SS " SCTP Socket Options"

.PP
The set of admissible SCTP socket options is by construction orthogonal to the sets of TCP, UDP, and generic \fIinet\fR options. Here are only options listed that are allowed for SCTP sockets.

.PP
Options can be set on the socket when calling \fIopen/1,2\fR, and changed when calling \fIconnect/4,5\fR or by calling \fIinet:setopts/2\fR.  They can be retrieved using \fIinet:getopts/2\fR.


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fI{mode, list|binary} | list | binary\fR\fR   - Determines the type of data returned from \fIrecv/1,2\fR or in \fIactive mode\fR data messages.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fI{active, false|true|once|N}\fR\fR 


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
If \fIfalse\fR (\fIpassive mode\fR, the default), the caller must do an explicit \fIrecv\fR call to retrieve the available data from the socket.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
If \fItrue|once|N\fR (\fIactive modes\fR) received data or events are sent to the owning process. See \fIopen/0..2\fR for the message format.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
If \fItrue\fR (fully \fIactive mode\fR) there is no flow control.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRNote that this can cause the message queue to overflow causing for example the virtual machine to run out of memory and crash.


.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
If \fIonce\fR, only one message is automatically placed in the message queue, and the mode resets to passive. This provides flow control and the possibility for the receiver to listen for incoming SCTP data interleaved with other inter-process messages.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
If \fIactive\fR is specified as an integer \fIN\fR in the range -32768 to 32767 (inclusive), that number is added to the socket's data messages counter. If the result of the addition is negative, the counter is set to \fI0\fR. Once the counter reaches \fI0\fR, either through the delivery of messages or by being explicitly set with \fIinet:setopts/2\fR, the socket mode resets to passive (\fI{active, false}\fR). When a socket in \fI{active, N}\fR mode transitions to passive mode, the message \fI{sctp_passive, Socket}\fR is sent to the controlling process to notify that if it wants to receive more data messages from the socket, it must call \fIinet:setopts/2\fR to set the socket back into an active mode.

.RE

.RE

{tos, integer()}
.RS 2
Sets the Type-Of-Service field on the IP datagrams that are sent, to the specified value. This effectively determines a prioritization policy for the outbound packets. The acceptable values are system-dependent.


.RE

{priority, integer()}
.RS 2
A protocol-independent equivalent of 
\fItos\fR above. Setting priority implies setting \fItos\fR as well.

.RE

{dontroute, true|false}
.RS 2
Defaults to 
\fIfalse\fR. If \fItrue\fR, the kernel does not send packets through any gateway, but only sends them to directly connected hosts.

.RE

{reuseaddr, true|false}
.RS 2
Defaults to 
\fIfalse\fR. If \fItrue\fR, the local binding address \fI{IP,Port}\fR of the socket can be reused immediately. No waiting in state \fICLOSE_WAIT\fR is performed (can be required for some types of servers).

.RE

{sndbuf, integer()}
.RS 2
The size, in bytes, of the OS kernel send buffer for this socket. Sending errors would occur for datagrams larger than 
\fIval(sndbuf)\fR. Setting this option also adjusts the size of the driver buffer (see \fIbuffer\fR above).

.RE

{recbuf, integer()}
.RS 2
The size, in bytes, of the OS kernel receive buffer for this socket. Sending errors would occur for datagrams larger than 
\fIval(recbuf)\fR. Setting this option also adjusts the size of the driver buffer (see \fIbuffer\fR above).

.RE

{non_block_send, boolean()}
.RS 2
A send call that would otherwise block (hang), will instead immediately return with e.g. 
\fI{error, eagain}\fR \fIif\fR this option has been set to \fItrue\fR. Defaults to \fIfalse\fR.

.RE

{sctp_module, module()}
.RS 2
Overrides which callback module is used. Defaults to 
\fIinet_sctp\fR for IPv4 and \fIinet6_sctp\fR for IPv6.

.RE


