.SH FUNCTIONS
.LP
.B
\fBabort(Socket, Assoc) -> ok | {error, inet:posix()}\fR
\fB               when\fR
\fB                   Socket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                   Assoc :: #sctp_assoc_change{}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Abort an association.

.PP
Abnormally terminates the association specified by \fIAssoc\fR, without flushing unsent data.  The socket itself remains open. Other associations opened on this socket are still valid, and the socket can be used in new associations.


.RE
.B
\fBclose(Socket) -> ok | {error, inet:posix()}\fR
\fB               when Socket :: sctp_socket().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Close an SCTP socket.

.PP
Closes the socket and all associations on it. The unsent data is flushed as for \fIeof/2\fR. The \fIclose/1\fR call is blocking depending of the value of the \fIlinger\fR socket [option]. If it is \fIfalse\fR or the linger time-out expires, the call returns and unsent data is flushed in the background.


.RE
.B
\fBconnect(Socket, SockAddr, Opts, Timeout) ->\fR
\fB                 {ok, #sctp_assoc_change{state :: comm_up}} |\fR
\fB                 {error, #sctp_assoc_change{state :: cant_assoc}} |\fR
\fB                 {error, inet:posix()}\fR
\fB                 when\fR
\fB                     Socket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                     SockAddr ::\fR
\fB                         socket:sockaddr_in() | socket:sockaddr_in6(),\fR
\fB                     Opts :: [Opt :: option()],\fR
\fB                     Timeout :: timeout();\fR
\fB             (Socket, Addr, Port, Opts) ->\fR
\fB                 {ok, #sctp_assoc_change{state :: comm_up}} |\fR
\fB                 {error, #sctp_assoc_change{state :: cant_assoc}} |\fR
\fB                 {error, inet:posix()}\fR
\fB                 when\fR
\fB                     Socket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                     Addr :: inet:ip_address() | inet:hostname(),\fR
\fB                     Port :: inet:port_number(),\fR
\fB                     Opts :: [Opt :: option()].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Establish an association with a peer.

.PP
With arguments \fIAddr\fR and \fIPort\fR, equivalent to \fIconnect(Socket, Addr, Port, Opts, infinity)\fR.

.PP
With arguments \fISockAddr\fR and \fIOpts\fR \fI(since OTP 24.3)\fR, equivalent to \fIconnect(Socket, Addr, Port, Opts, Timeout)\fR where \fIAddr\fR and \fIPort\fR are extracted from \fISockAddr\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBconnect(Socket, Addr, Port, Opts, Timeout) ->\fR
\fB                 {ok, #sctp_assoc_change{state :: comm_up}} |\fR
\fB                 {error, #sctp_assoc_change{state :: cant_assoc}} |\fR
\fB                 {error, inet:posix()}\fR
\fB                 when\fR
\fB                     Socket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                     Addr :: inet:ip_address() | inet:hostname(),\fR
\fB                     Port :: inet:port_number(),\fR
\fB                     Opts :: [Opt :: option()],\fR
\fB                     Timeout :: timeout().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Establish an association with a peer.

.PP
Establishes a new association for socket \fISocket\fR, with the peer (SCTP server socket) specified by \fIAddr\fR and \fIPort\fR. \fITimeout\fR, is expressed in milliseconds. A socket can be associated with multiple peers. The socket has to be of type \fIseqpacket\fR.

.PP
\fBWARNING: \fRUsing a value of \fITimeout\fR less than the maximum time taken by the OS to establish an association (around 4.5 minutes if the default values from RFC 4960 are used), can result in inconsistent or incorrect return values. This is especially relevant for associations sharing the same \fISocket\fR (that is, source address and port), as the controlling process blocks until \fIconnect/*\fR returns. \fIconnect_init/*\fR provides an alternative without this limitation.


.PP
\fB \fR\fB\fI#sctp_assoc_change{}\fR\fR

.PP
The result of \fIconnect/*\fR is an \fI#sctp_assoc_change{}\fR event that contains, in particular, the new Association ID: l

.IP
.nf
#sctp_assoc_change{
      state             = atom(),
      error             = integer(),
      outbound_streams  = integer(),
      inbound_streams   = integer(),
      assoc_id          = assoc_id()
}

.fi

.PP
The number of outbound and inbound streams for the association can be set by giving an \fIsctp_initmsg\fR option to \fIconnect\fR as in:

.IP
.nf
connect(Socket, Ip, Port>,
      [{sctp_initmsg,#sctp_initmsg{num_ostreams=OutStreams,
                                   max_instreams=MaxInStreams}}])

.fi

.PP
All options \fIOpt\fR are set on the socket before the association is attempted. If an option record has undefined field values, the options record is first read from the socket for those values. In effect, \fIOpt\fR option records only need to define field values to change before connecting.

.PP
The returned \fIoutbound_streams\fR and \fIinbound_streams\fR are the number of stream on the socket. These can be different from the requested values (\fIOutStreams\fR and \fIMaxInStreams\fR, respectively), if the peer requires lower values.

.PP
\fIstate\fR can have the following values:

comm_up
.RS 2
Association is successfully established. This indicates a successful completion of 
\fIconnect\fR.

.RE

cant_assoc
.RS 2
The association cannot be established (
\fIconnect/*\fR failure).

.RE

.PP
Other states do not normally occur in the output from \fIconnect/*\fR. Rather, they can occur in \fI#sctp_assoc_change{}\fR events received instead of data from \fIrecv/*\fR calls or socket messages. All of them indicate losing the association because of various error conditions, and are listed here for the sake of completeness:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIcomm_lost\fR\fR

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIrestart\fR\fR

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIshutdown_comp\fR\fR

.RE

.PP
The field \fIerror\fR can provide more detailed diagnostics.  Its value can be converted into a string using \fIerror_string/1\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBconnect_init(Socket, SockAddr, Opts, Timeout) ->\fR
\fB                      ok | {error, inet:posix()}\fR
\fB                      when\fR
\fB                          Socket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                          SockAddr ::\fR
\fB                              socket:sockaddr_in() |\fR
\fB                              socket:sockaddr_in6(),\fR
\fB                          Opts :: [option()],\fR
\fB                          Timeout :: timeout();\fR
\fB                  (Socket, Addr, Port, Opts) ->\fR
\fB                      ok | {error, inet:posix()}\fR
\fB                      when\fR
\fB                          Socket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                          Addr :: inet:ip_address() | inet:hostname(),\fR
\fB                          Port :: inet:port_number(),\fR
\fB                          Opts :: [option()].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Start establishing an association with a peer.

.PP
With arguments \fIAddr\fR and \fIPort\fR, equivalent to \fIconnect_init(Socket, Addr, Port, Opts, infinity)\fR.

.PP
With arguments \fISockAddr\fR and \fIOpts\fR \fI(since OTP 24.3)\fR, equivalent to \fIconnect_init(Socket, Addr, Port, Opts, Timeout)\fR where \fIAddr\fR and \fIPort\fR are extracted from \fISockAddr\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBconnect_init(Socket, Addr, Port, Opts, Timeout) ->\fR
\fB                      ok | {error, inet:posix()}\fR
\fB                      when\fR
\fB                          Socket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                          Addr :: inet:ip_address() | inet:hostname(),\fR
\fB                          Port :: inet:port_number(),\fR
\fB                          Opts :: [option()],\fR
\fB                          Timeout :: timeout().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Start establishing an association with a peer.

.PP
Initiates a new association for socket \fISocket\fR, with the peer (SCTP server socket) specified by \fIAddr\fR and \fIPort\fR.

.PP
The fundamental difference between this API and \fIconnect/*\fR is that the return value is that of the underlying OS \fIconnect(2)\fR system call. If \fIok\fR is returned, the operation has been succesfully initiated, and the final result result of the association establishment is sent to the socket owner (controlling process) as an \fI#sctp_assoc_change{}\fR event. The socket owner must be prepared to receive this, the \fIrecv/*\fR call has to be polled, depending on the value of the active option.

.PP
The parameters are as described for \fIconnect/*\fR, except the \fITimeout\fR value since for this function, the time-out only applies to the name resolving of \fIAddr\fR when it is a \fIinet:hostname/0\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBconnectx_init(Socket, SockAddrs, Opts) ->\fR
\fB                       {ok, assoc_id()} | {error, inet:posix()}\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           Socket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                           SockAddrs ::\fR
\fB                               [{inet:ip_address(), inet:port_number()} |\fR
\fB                                inet:family_address() |\fR
\fB                                socket:sockaddr_in() |\fR
\fB                                socket:sockaddr_in6()],\fR
\fB                           Opts :: [option()].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Start establishing an association with a peer (multiple addresses).

.PP
Similar to \fIconnectx_init/5\fR except using socket addresses, and not having a \fITimeout\fR. Since the addresses do not need lookup and the connect is non-blocking this call returns immediately.

.PP
The value of each socket address \fIport\fR must be the same or zero. At least one socket address must have a non-zero \fIport\fR


.RE
.B
\fBconnectx_init(Socket, Addrs, Port, Opts, Timeout) ->\fR
\fB                       {ok, assoc_id()} | {error, inet:posix()}\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           Socket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                           Addrs ::\fR
\fB                               [inet:ip_address() | inet:hostname()],\fR
\fB                           Port :: inet:port_number() | atom(),\fR
\fB                           Opts :: [option()],\fR
\fB                           Timeout :: timeout().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Start establishing an association with a peer (multiple addresses).

.PP
Initiates a new association for socket \fISocket\fR, with the peer (SCTP server socket) specified by \fIAddrs\fR and \fIPort\fR.

.PP
This API is similar to \fIconnect_init/*\fR except the underlying OS \fIsctp_connectx(3)\fR system call is used, that accepts multiple destination addresses.

.PP
If successful, the association ID is returned which will be received in a subsequent \fI#sctp_assoc_change{}\fR event.

.PP
The parameters are as described in \fIconnect_init/5\fR

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThis API allows the OS to use all Addrs when establishing an association, but does not guarantee it will. Therefore, if the connection fails, the user may want to rotate the order of addresses for a subsequent call.



.RE
.B
\fBcontrolling_process(Socket, Pid) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                             when\fR
\fB                                 Socket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                                 Pid :: pid(),\fR
\fB                                 Reason ::\fR
\fB                                     closed | not_owner | badarg |\fR
\fB                                     inet:posix().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Change the controlling process (owner) of a socket.

.PP
Assigns a new controlling process \fIPid\fR to \fISocket\fR. See \fIgen_udp:controlling_process/2\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBeof(Socket, Assoc) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB             when\fR
\fB                 Socket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                 Assoc :: #sctp_assoc_change{},\fR
\fB                 Reason :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Terminate an association gracefully.

.PP
Gracefully terminates the association specified by \fIAssoc\fR, flushing all unsent data. The socket itself remains open.  Other associations opened on this socket are still valid.  The socket can be used in new associations.


.RE
.B
\fBerror_string(ErrorNumber) -> ok | string() | unknown_error\fR
\fB                      when ErrorNumber :: integer().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Translate an error number into a string or atom.

.PP
Translates an SCTP error number from, for example, \fI#sctp_remote_error{}\fR or \fI#sctp_send_failed{}\fR into an explanatory string, or into one of the atoms \fIok\fR for no error, or \fIunknown_error\fR for an unrecognized integer.


.RE
.B
\fBlisten(Socket, IsServer) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    Socket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                    IsServer :: boolean(),\fR
\fB                    Reason :: term();\fR
\fB            (Socket, Backlog) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    Socket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                    Backlog :: integer(),\fR
\fB                    Reason :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Make an SCTP socket listen to incoming associations.

.PP
The socket will listen on the IP address(es) and port number it is bound to.

.PP
For type \fIseqpacket\fR, sockets (the default), the argument\fIIsServer\fR must be a \fIboolean/0\fR.  In contrast to \fIstream\fR sockets, there is no listening queue length.  If \fIIsServer\fR is \fItrue\fR, the socket accepts new associations, that is, it becomes an SCTP server socket.

.PP
For type \fIstream\fR sockets, the argument \fIBacklog\fR sets the backlog queue length just like for TCP.


.RE
.B
\fBopen(Port) -> {ok, Socket} | {error, inet:posix()}\fR
\fB              when Port :: inet:port_number(), Socket :: sctp_socket();\fR
\fB          (Opts) -> {ok, Socket} | {error, inet:posix()}\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  Opts :: [Opt],\fR
\fB                  Opt ::\fR
\fB                      {ifaddr, IP | SockAddr} |\fR
\fB                      {ip, IP} |\fR
\fB                      {port, Port} |\fR
\fB                      inet:address_family() |\fR
\fB                      {type, SockType} |\fR
\fB                      {netns, file:filename_all()} |\fR
\fB                      {bind_to_device, binary()} |\fR
\fB                      option(),\fR
\fB                  IP :: inet:ip_address() | any | loopback,\fR
\fB                  SockAddr ::\fR
\fB                      socket:sockaddr_in() | socket:sockaddr_in6(),\fR
\fB                  Port :: inet:port_number(),\fR
\fB                  SockType :: seqpacket | stream,\fR
\fB                  Socket :: sctp_socket().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Create an SCTP socket.

.PP
With argument \fIPort\fR, equivalent to\fIopen([{port, Port}]\fR.

.PP
Creates an SCTP socket and binds it to the local addresses specified by all \fI{ip,IP}\fR (or synonymously \fI{ifaddr,IP}\fR) options (this feature is called SCTP multi-homing). The default \fIIP\fR and \fIPort\fR are \fIany\fR and \fI0\fR, meaning bind to all local addresses on any free port.

.PP
It is also possible to use \fI{ifaddr, SockAddr}\fR, in which case it takes precedence over the \fIip\fR and \fIport\fR options. These options can however be used to update the address and port of ifaddr (if they occur after ifaddr in the options list), although this is not recommended.

.PP
Other options:

inet6
.RS 2
Sets up the socket for IPv6.


.RE

inet
.RS 2
Sets up the socket for IPv4. This is the default.


.RE

.PP
A default set of socket options is used. In particular, the socket is opened in binary and passive mode, with SockType \fIseqpacket\fR, and with reasonably large kernel and driver buffers.

.PP
When the socket is in passive mode, data can be received through the \fIrecv/1,2\fR calls.

.PP
When the socket is in active mode, received data is delivered to the controlling process as messages:

.IP
.nf
{sctp, Socket, FromIP, FromPort, {AncData, Data}}

.fi

.PP
Error-related events - such as \fI#sctp_send_failed{}\fR, \fI#sctp_pdapi_event{}\fR, and \fI#sctp_remote_error{}\fR - are also delivered to the controlling process as messages, but use a different tuple tag:

.IP
.nf
{sctp_error, Socket, FromIP, FromPort, {AncData, Data}}

.fi

.PP
See \fIrecv/1,2\fR for a description of the message fields.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThis message format unfortunately differs slightly from the \fIgen_udp\fR message format with ancillary data, and from the \fIrecv/1,2\fR return tuple format.



.RE
.B
\fBpeeloff(Socket, Assoc) -> {ok, NewSocket} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                 when\fR
\fB                     Socket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                     Assoc :: #sctp_assoc_change{} | assoc_id(),\fR
\fB                     NewSocket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                     Reason :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Branch off an association into a new socket of type \fIstream\fR.

.PP
The existing association \fIAssoc\fR in the socket \fISocket\fR (that has to be of type \fIseqpacket\fR; one-to-many style) is branched off into a new socket \fINewSocket\fR of type \fIstream\fR (one-to-one style).

.PP
The existing association argument \fIAssoc\fR can be a \fI#sctp_assoc_change{}\fR record as returned from, for example, \fIrecv/*\fR, \fIconnect/*\fR, or from a listening socket in active mode. It can also be just the field \fIassoc_id\fR \fIinteger/0\fR from such a record.


.RE
.B
\fBrecv(Socket, Timeout) ->\fR
\fB              {ok, {FromIP, FromPort, AncData, Data}} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  Socket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                  Timeout :: timeout(),\fR
\fB                  FromIP :: inet:ip_address(),\fR
\fB                  FromPort :: inet:port_number(),\fR
\fB                  AncData ::\fR
\fB                      [#sctp_sndrcvinfo{} | inet:ancillary_data()],\fR
\fB                  Data ::\fR
\fB                      binary() |\fR
\fB                      string() |\fR
\fB                      #sctp_sndrcvinfo{} |\fR
\fB                      #sctp_assoc_change{} |\fR
\fB                      #sctp_paddr_change{} |\fR
\fB                      #sctp_adaptation_event{},\fR
\fB                  Reason ::\fR
\fB                      inet:posix() |\fR
\fB                      #sctp_send_failed{} |\fR
\fB                      #sctp_paddr_change{} |\fR
\fB                      #sctp_pdapi_event{} |\fR
\fB                      #sctp_remote_error{} |\fR
\fB                      #sctp_shutdown_event{}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Receive a \fIData\fR message.

.PP
Receives the \fIData\fR message from any association of the socket. If the receive times out, \fI{error,timeout}\fR is returned. The default time-out is \fIinfinity\fR. \fIFromIP\fR and \fIFromPort\fR indicate the address of the sender.

.PP
\fIAncData\fR is a list of ancillary data items received with the main \fIData\fR. This list can be empty, or contain a single \fI#sctp_sndrcvinfo{}\fR record, if receiving ancillary data is enabled (see option \fIsctp_events\fR). Per default, it is enabled, as such ancillary data provides an easy way to determine the association and stream over which the message was received. (An alternative way is to get the association ID from \fIFromIP\fR and \fIFromPort\fR using socket option \fIsctp_get_peer_addr_info\fR, but this does still not give the stream number).

.PP
\fIAncData\fR may also contain ancillary data from the socket options \fIrecvtos\fR, \fIrecvtclass\fR or \fIrecvttl\fR, if that is supported for the socket by the platform.

.PP
The \fIData\fR received can, depending on the socket mode be a \fIbinary/0\fR or a \fIlist/0\fR of bytes (integers in the range \fI0\fR through \fI255\fR), or it can be an SCTP event.

.PP
\fB Possible SCTP events\fR


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fI#sctp_sndrcvinfo{}\fR

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fI#sctp_assoc_change{}\fR

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.IP
.nf
#sctp_paddr_change{
      addr      = {ip_address(),port()},
      state     = atom(),
      error     = integer(),
      assoc_id  = assoc_id()
}

.fi

.PP
Indicates change of the status of the IP address of the peer specified by \fIaddr\fR within association \fIassoc_id\fR. Possible values of \fIstate\fR (mostly self-explanatory) include:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIaddr_unreachable\fR\fR

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIaddr_available\fR\fR

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIaddr_removed\fR\fR

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIaddr_added\fR\fR

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIaddr_made_prim\fR\fR

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIaddr_confirmed\fR\fR

.RE

.PP
In case of an error (for example, \fIaddr_unreachable\fR), the field \fIerror\fR provides more diagnostics. In such cases, event \fI#sctp_paddr_change{}\fR is automatically converted into an \fIerror\fR term returned by \fIrecv\fR. The \fIerror\fR field value can be converted into a string using \fIerror_string/1\fR.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.IP
.nf
#sctp_send_failed{
      flags     = true | false,
      error     = integer(),
      info      = #sctp_sndrcvinfo{},
      assoc_id  = assoc_id()
      data      = binary()
}

.fi

.PP
The sender can receive this event if a send operation fails.

flags
.RS 2
A Boolean specifying if the data has been transmitted over the wire.


.RE

error
.RS 2
Provides extended diagnostics, use 
\fIerror_string/1\fR.

.RE

info
.RS 2
The original 
\fI#sctp_sndrcvinfo{}\fR record used in the failed \fIsend/*\fR.

.RE

data
.RS 2
The whole original data chunk attempted to be sent.


.RE

.PP
In the current implementation of the Erlang/SCTP binding, this event is internally converted into an \fIerror\fR term returned by \fIrecv/*\fR.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.IP
.nf
#sctp_adaptation_event{
      adaptation_ind = integer(),
      assoc_id       = assoc_id()
}

.fi

.PP
Delivered when a peer sends an adaptation layer indication parameter (configured through option \fIsctp_adaptation_layer\fR). Notie that with the current implementation of the Erlang/SCTP binding, this event is disabled by default.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.IP
.nf
#sctp_pdapi_event{
      indication = sctp_partial_delivery_aborted,
      assoc_id   = assoc_id()
}

.fi

.PP
A partial delivery failure. In the current implementation of the Erlang/SCTP binding, this event is internally converted into an \fIerror\fR term returned by \fIrecv/*\fR.

.RE


.RE
.B
\fBsend(Socket, SndRcvInfo, Data) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  Socket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                  SndRcvInfo :: #sctp_sndrcvinfo{},\fR
\fB                  Data :: binary() | iolist(),\fR
\fB                  Reason :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Send a \fIData\fR message, full-featured.

.PP
Sends the \fIData\fR message with all sending parameters from a \fI#sctp_sndrcvinfo{}\fR record. This way, the user can specify the PPID (passed to the remote end) and context (passed to the local SCTP layer), which can be used, for example, for error identification.  However, such a fine grained user control is rarely required. The function \fIsend/4\fR is sufficient for most applications.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRSend is normally blocking, but if the socket option \fInon_block_send\fR is set to true, the function will return with e.g. {error, eagain} in the case when the function would otherwise block. It is then up to the user to try again later.



.RE
.B
\fBsend(Socket, Assoc, Stream, Data) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  Socket :: sctp_socket(),\fR
\fB                  Assoc :: #sctp_assoc_change{} | assoc_id(),\fR
\fB                  Stream :: integer(),\fR
\fB                  Data :: binary() | iolist(),\fR
\fB                  Reason :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Send a data message.

.PP
Sends a \fIData\fR message on the association \fIAssoc\fR and \fIStream\fR.

.PP
\fIAssoc\fR can be specified with a \fI#sctp_assoc_change{}\fR record from an association establishment, or as the \fIassoc_id/0\fR \fIinteger/0\fR field value.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRSend is normally blocking, but if the socket option \fInon_block_send\fR is set to true, the function will return with e.g. {error, eagain} in the case when the function would otherwise block. It is then up to the user to try again later.



.RE
